General Rule :
selector{
  property1 : value1;
  property2 : value2;
}

Ways to Write :
                Inline :
          <li style="color:white">Playing Cricket</li>
                Style Tag:
          <style>
            h1{
              color : blue;
            }
          </style>
     
Colors : # + 6 digit Hexadecimal Number, rgb(a,b,c) {0 <= a,b,c < 256}

Some Properties and corresponding Values:
1. background : red
2. background : url(url of image)
3. background-repeat : no-repeat;
4. background-size : cover 
5. border : <width(in px), style, color>
  style = {solid, dashed}

-> Give id's to attributes in order to diffrenciate them.
  To use id write #<name of id>{attributes}
-> Instead of id apply class for styling multiple elements.
  To use class write .<name of class>{attributes}
-> checked attribute inside input saves the checkbottons in the page.

https://code.tutsplus.com/tutorials/the-30-css-selectors-you-must-memorize--net-16048

Some More Selectors :

*{}                      -            Selects the entire web page         [Star selector]
li a(.hello){}           -            every anchor tag inside li tag.     [Descendent selector]
li + a {}                -            style all the siblings after tag    [Adjacent selector]
a[href = ""]             -            style all attributes inside a tag.  [Attribute selector]
ul:nth-of-type(2)        -            style all 2nd in ul tag.            [nth of selector]

Fonts:
p {
font-family: Arial;
}
h1{
font-size: 200px;
}
p{
font-weight: x*100 xE(1,8)
}
p{
line-height: 2;
}
p{
text-align: centre;
}
p{
text-decoration: underline;
}
See Google fonts.
